1.  Record whether or not the customer responded.
2.  Give the customer a call and, simultaneously, record if they are willing to talk.
3. Record if they are willing to talk without calling them. (This represents the scenario when the customer reaches out proactively)


If the customer has responded (path 1), confirming the call date and time, and sending them an email occur concurrently. If the customer was called (path 2), and willing to talk, the same concurrent actions happen, confirming the call date and time and sending an email. If the customer was willing to talk (Path 2 and Path 3), then these steps are skipped. 

Following any or all of these three paths, the user identifies the root cause of any issues and describes their value-increasing ideas. These steps happen one after the other, regardless of whether the customer responded or if there was a call.

After describing the ideas, there are two paths that, again, can be pursued independently, simultaneously, or in any combination: recording the customer's decision, and thanking them for their time and feedback.

Regardless of which of these two paths are taken, the user proceeds to ask the customer if they have any other concerns.  Afterward, noting down important learnings and sending them to appropriate managers are done in parallel. Finally, the process ends.

The review of the business plan leads to the review of team chemistry.  Then, the expertise review, and the team chemistry review, both inform a final assessment. This final assessment leads to another set of parallel tasks: checking the cash flow and checking the exit strategy.

The results of the cash flow and exit strategy checks are then combined to project the market share, which is the final step before checking patents and concluding the process.
